{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585761"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15011"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15011"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.82,0.05,0.09,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7699"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66851"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7699"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15011"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52305"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18816"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66851"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDifferent classes of antibiotics target bacterial protein synthesis by binding to specific ribosomal subunits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibiotics inhibits protein synthesis by binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aminoglycosides","Chloramphenicol","Erythromycin","Linezolid","Clindamycin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAminoglycosides\u003C/strong\u003E bind to the 30S ribosomal subunit, causing misreading of messenger RNA and inhibiting bacterial protein synthesis. This leads to production of defective proteins and bacterial cell death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other antibiotics act on the 50S ribosomal subunit through different mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChloramphenicol\u003C/strong\u003E prevents peptide bond formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E and other macrolides block the peptide exit tunnel\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELinezolid\u003C/strong\u003E prevents formation of the initiation complex\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E interferes with peptidyl transferase activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile these antibiotics all inhibit protein synthesis, they do so through distinct mechanisms at different ribosomal targets.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aminoglycosides inhibit protein synthesis by binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit, causing misreading of messenger RNA","Most protein synthesis inhibitors (chloramphenicol, macrolides, linezolid, clindamycin) act on the 50S ribosomal subunit","Different antibiotic classes that target the 50S subunit have distinct mechanisms of action at this site"],"references":["Hauser, A. (2018). Antibiotic basics for clinicians. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Serio AW, Keepers T, Andrews L, Krause KM. Aminoglycoside Revival: Review of a Historically Important Class of Antimicrobials Undergoing Rejuvenation. EcoSal Plus. 2018 Nov;8(1). doi: 10.1128/ecosalplus.ESP-0002-2018. PMID: 30447062."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52305"}},"question":{"data":